{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:07:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15796"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15796"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.02,0.09,0.01,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8487"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104981"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8487","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8487"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15796"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87369"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"7984"},{"type":"tags","id":"8758"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34946"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104981"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice for review of recurrent abscesses in her axillae and groin areas. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and takes metformin and gliclazide. She smokes 20 cigarettes per day. She is a fervent cyclist, going for 3 hour long trips each weekend and at least an hour ride each day in lycra.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are lesions similar to the image of her left axilla (Image) in both axillae and groin areas. There is no evidence of active infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following lifestyle changes should be advised to reduce the severity of disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cessation of smoking","Bleach baths daily","Applying moisturiser daily","Daily exposure to sunlight for 10 minutes","Avoiding tight clothing"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild Hurley stage II hidradenitis suppurativa, characterised by recurrent abscesses with sinus tract formation and scarring. Hidradenitis suppurativa is a chronic inflammatory skin condition affecting apocrine gland-bearing areas such as the axillae, groin, and inframammary regions affecting patients from puberty to adulthood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECessation of smoking\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important lifestyle modification for patients with hidradenitis suppurativa. Smoking is a well-established trigger and exacerbating factor for the condition. Studies have shown that smokers have more severe disease and poorer response to treatment. Nicotine may enhance follicular occlusion and stimulate inflammatory cytokine production, worsening the disease process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBleach baths daily\u003C/strong\u003E are not specifically recommended for hidradenitis suppurativa management. While dilute bleach baths may be used in some skin conditions like atopic dermatitis to reduce bacterial colonization, there is no strong evidence supporting their routine use in hidradenitis suppurativa. They may even cause irritation in inflamed areas.  Antiseptic washes such as benozyl peroxide 5% washes can be used when bathing in mild HS, but is insufficient for moderate HS. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApplying moisturiser daily\u003C/strong\u003E is not specifically indicated for hidradenitis suppurativa management. While good skin hygiene is important, there is no evidence that regular moisturising reduces disease severity or prevents flares in hidradenitis suppurativa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDaily exposure to sunlight for 10 minutes\u003C/strong\u003E has not been shown to have any beneficial effect on hidradenitis suppurativa. Unlike some other inflammatory skin conditions like psoriasis, hidradenitis suppurativa does not typically respond to ultraviolet light therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoiding tight clothing\u003C/strong\u003E and wearing loose clothing may provide some symptomatic relief by reducing friction and irritation in affected areas, but there is limited evidence that this significantly impacts disease severity or progression compared to smoking cessation.  Smoking cessation as discussed is a stronger trigger for flares and in affecting response to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFurthermore, weight loss has shown to affect the course of HS and should be encouraged for patients who present with HS.  Patients should also be screened for hyperlipidemia and depression which is also associated with HS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Smoking cessation is the most important lifestyle modification for patients with hidradenitis suppurativa.","Hidradenitis suppurativa is a chronic inflammatory skin condition affecting apocrine gland-bearing areas.","Hurley stage II hidradenitis suppurativa is characterised by recurrent abscesses with sinus tract formation and scarring."],"references":["Vekic DA, Cains GD. Hidradenitis suppurativa - Management, comorbidities and monitoring. Aust Fam Physician. 2017;46(8):584-588. PMID: 28787558.","Smith S et al. Management of hidradenitis suppurativa: an Australasian consensus statement | DermNet NZ [Internet]. dermnetnz.org. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/hidradenitis-suppurativa-guidelines","Vekic D, Cains G. Hidradenitis suppurativa \u2013 Management, comorbidities and monitoring [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. 2017:46 (8). Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2017/august/hidradenitis-suppurativa-management-comorbidities"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87369"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15796"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21746"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21746"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kg940K7RBvJ4Sb6JXJiFhJXosYUPll.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Kg940K7RBvJ4Sb6JXJiFhJXosYUPll.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87369"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-06T12:50:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-06T12:50:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8487"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104981"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"20","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/20"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4c","name":"Plastic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"dat